included.description:
The Open Medicine Institute is an international organization that joins bioinformatics and traditional clinical methods to investigate the causes and factors related to Lyme Disease and Chronic Fatigue Syndrome. With the OpenMedNet platform where patients can collect, curate and share their own medical data they are changing pace of and patient access to research interventions. 

While at OMI, I was project lead of a genetic screening initiative directed at the Jewish community. Working with a multi-national team of community engagement consultants, UI/UX designers, an engineering team, and a claims consultant, I built marketing research plans, performed revenue analyses on claims data, conducted patient care management and planned two successful patient screening events. In the short span of, one year, I was able to understand the challenges of the healthcare market and deliver outstanding work with only a basic understanding of the healthcare system and business management.

Within the company,  I proactively was attentive to procedural detail and documented business operations. I conducted process optimization studies across the laboratory workflow using the Lean Six Sigma method and proposed a total productive maintenance structure that improved existing communications between employees at the research institute and the out-patient clinics, and resulted in time and cost reductions in healthcare delivery.

included.summary:
Srishti is a second year masters student at the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor studying Health Informatics at the Schools of Public Health and Information. Health informatics is a nascent field that focuses on bringing to bear the rigor and evidence-based informatics approach on public health intervention development and implementation. Working along side her colleagues from all over the world with varying specialities, Srishti is known for her collaborative optimistic mindset and go-getter attitude. 

Srishti specializes in bringing practical solutions to wicked problems in the healthcare space and is working toward improving her technical proficiency in Python, SQL and R while expanding her knowledge of global health and how informatics approaches can be used to support and optimize global public health intervention initiatives.
